        <link rel="schema.DC" href="https://purl.org/DC/elements/1.0/" /><meta name="citation_journal_title" content="RadioGraphics" /><meta name="dc.Title" content="Ductal Carcinoma in Situ of the Breast: MR Imaging Findings with Histopathologic Correlation1" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Mahmud  Mossa-Basha" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Gina M.  Fundaro" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Biren A.  Shah" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Sharif  Ali" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Milan V.  Pantelic" /><meta name="dc.Description" content="MR imaging evaluation of seven biopsy-proved cases of DCIS of the breast is discussed, with emphasis on imaging techniques and correlation of imaging findings with relevant histopathologic features." /><meta name="Description" content="MR imaging evaluation of seven biopsy-proved cases of DCIS of the breast is discussed, with emphasis on imaging techniques and correlation of imaging findings with relevant histopathologic features." /><meta name="dc.Description" content="Ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS) is a noninvasive malignancy that is commonly encountered at routine breast imaging. It may be a primary tumor or may be seen in association with other focal higher-g..." /><meta name="Description" content="Ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS) is a noninvasive malignancy that is commonly encountered at routine breast imaging. It may be a primary tumor or may be seen in association with other focal higher-g..." /><meta name="dc.Publisher" content="Radiological Society of North America" /><meta name="dc.Date" scheme="WTN8601" content="2010-10-06" /><meta name="dc.Type" content="research-article" /><meta name="dc.Format" content="text/HTML" /><meta name="dc.Identifier" scheme="publisher-id" content="105510" /><meta name="dc.Identifier" scheme="doi" content="10.1148/rg.306105510" /><meta name="dc.Source" content="https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.306105510" /><meta name="dc.Language" content="en" /><meta name="dc.Coverage" content="w